To introduce someone to jazz and showcase the genre's evolution, here's a chronologically ordered playlist of seven significant tracks, each with its own Wikipedia page:

1. **"St. Louis Blues" – W.C. Handy (1914)**  
   A cornerstone in early jazz, this composition blends blues and ragtime, influencing countless jazz musicians.  
   [Wikipedia: "St. Louis Blues"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Louis_Blues)

2. **"Body and Soul" – Coleman Hawkins (1939)**  
   Hawkins' rendition is renowned for its improvisation, marking a departure from swing to more complex bebop styles.  
   [Wikipedia: "Body and Soul"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_and_Soul_(1930_song))

3. **"Take Five" – The Dave Brubeck Quartet (1959)**  
   Composed by Paul Desmond, this track is notable for its distinctive 5/4 time signature, contributing to the cool jazz movement.  
   [Wikipedia: "Take Five"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Take_Five)

4. **"So What" – Miles Davis (1959)**  
   A prime example of modal jazz, this piece from the album *Kind of Blue* showcases Davis's innovative approach.  
   [Wikipedia: "So What"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/So_What_(Miles_Davis_composition))

5. **"Giant Steps" – John Coltrane (1960)**  
   Known for its rapid chord changes, this composition is a testament to Coltrane's virtuosity and the complexities of hard bop.  
   [Wikipedia: "Giant Steps"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giant_Steps_(composition))

6. **"Chameleon" – Herbie Hancock (1973)**  
   A fusion of jazz, funk, and electronic music, this track reflects the genre's adaptability and Hancock's experimental spirit.  
   [Wikipedia: "Chameleon"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chameleon_(composition))

7. **"Birdland" – Weather Report (1977)**  
   This jazz fusion piece pays homage to the famed jazz club and showcases the genre's evolution into the late 20th century.  
   [Wikipedia: "Birdland"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birdland_(song))

This selection offers a glimpse into the rich tapestry of jazz history, highlighting pivotal moments and artists who have shaped the genre.

